        body: "Central tendency summarises a dataset with a single representative value. Arithmetic Mean (AM): sum of all values divided by count. Simple AM = ΣX/n. Weighted AM = Σ(w×X) / Σw. Most sensitive to extreme values (outliers). Median: the middle value when data is sorted. For n observations: if n is odd, median = [(n+1)/2]th value; if even, average of (n/2)th and (n/2+1)th. Not affected by outliers — preferred for skewed distributions (e.g., income data). Mode: most frequently occurring value. Can be absent or multiple (bimodal, multimodal). Relationship in a moderately skewed distribution: Mean − Mode ≈ 3(Mean − Median). Geometric Mean (GM): ⁿ√(X₁ × X₂ × … × Xₙ) — used for averaging growth rates, index returns. Harmonic Mean (HM): n / Σ(1/Xᵢ) — used for averaging rates (e.g., average speed, average cost per unit).",
