        body: "Correlation measures the direction and strength of linear relationship between two variables. Pearson Correlation Coefficient (r): r = Σ[(Xᵢ−X̄)(Yᵢ−Ȳ)] / √[Σ(Xᵢ−X̄)² × Σ(Yᵢ−Ȳ)²]. Range: −1 ≤ r ≤ +1. r = +1: perfect positive; r = −1: perfect negative; r = 0: no linear relationship. Spearman Rank Correlation: r_s = 1 − (6Σd²) / [n(n²−1)] where d = rank difference. Used when data is ordinal or non-normal. Coefficient of Determination r²: proportion of variation in Y explained by X. r² = 0.85 means X explains 85% of variation in Y. Linear Regression: Y = a + bX. Slope b = r × (σ_Y / σ_X) = Σ(Xᵢ−X̄)(Yᵢ−Ȳ) / Σ(Xᵢ−X̄)². Intercept a = Ȳ − b×X̄.",
        highlight: "r = Σ[(X−X̄)(Y−Ȳ)] / √[Σ(X−X̄)²·Σ(Y−Ȳ)²] | r²: variation explained | b = Σ(X−X̄)(Y−Ȳ)/Σ(X−X̄)² | a = Ȳ − bX̄"
