        kind: "concept",
        title: "Index Numbers — Measuring Price Level Changes",
        body: "An index number measures the relative change in a variable (price, quantity, value) over time. Base year index = 100. Price Indices: Laspeyres Price Index (LPI): uses BASE year quantities as weights. LPI = [Σ(P₁×Q₀) / Σ(P₀×Q₀)] × 100. Biased upward (assumes consumers keep buying same basket even as prices change). Paasche Price Index (PPI): uses CURRENT year quantities as weights. PPI = [Σ(P₁×Q₁) / Σ(P₀×Q₁)] × 100. Biased downward (reflects substitution towards cheaper goods). Fisher's Ideal Index: geometric mean of Laspeyres and Paasche. Fisher = √(LPI × PPI). Unbiased — satisfies both time reversal and factor reversal tests. India's CPI: uses Laspeyres method with weights from household consumption surveys.",
        highlight: "Laspeyres = Σ(P₁Q₀)/Σ(P₀Q₀)×100 (base qty wts) | Paasche = Σ(P₁Q₁)/Σ(P₀Q₁)×100 (current qty wts) | Fisher = √(L×P) | LPI ≥ Fisher ≥ PPI"
