        body: "Interest Rate Parity (IRP) links interest rate differentials to forward exchange rates. Covered IRP (CIRP): The forward rate is set so that investing domestically and investing abroad with a forward cover yield the same return — eliminating covered interest arbitrage. Forward Rate = Spot × (1 + r_d) / (1 + r_f). If CIRP does not hold, arbitrageurs will exploit the difference until parity is restored. Uncovered IRP (UIRP): The expected future spot rate adjusts to eliminate expected excess returns — without a forward hedge. UIRP links expected exchange rate changes to interest differentials. Fisher Effect: Nominal rate = Real rate + Expected inflation. International Fisher Effect: The currency of the higher-nominal-rate country is expected to depreciate by the interest rate differential.",
