        body: "Banks maintain accounts with each other to facilitate international payments and settlements. The naming convention depends on the perspective: NOSTRO Account ('Our account with you') — an account maintained by an Indian bank (e.g., SBI) with a foreign bank (e.g., Citibank New York) in foreign currency (USD). SBI's USD account at Citibank NY is SBI's NOSTRO account. VOSTRO Account ('Your account with us') — the same account from the foreign bank's perspective. Citibank NY's rupee account at SBI Mumbai is Citibank's VOSTRO account (and SBI's NOSTRO in reverse). LORO Account ('Their account') — used when bank A refers to the account that bank B maintains with bank C. Used in transactions involving a third correspondent bank.",
