        body: "Operational Risk (OpRisk) is the risk of loss resulting from inadequate or failed internal processes, people, systems, or from external events. This definition includes legal risk but excludes strategic and reputational risk. Basel II/III defines seven event-type categories: (1) Internal Fraud, (2) External Fraud, (3) Employment Practices & Workplace Safety, (4) Clients, Products & Business Practices, (5) Damage to Physical Assets, (6) Business Disruption & System Failures, (7) Execution, Delivery & Process Management. Banks must maintain a Loss Data Collection (LDC) database of all operational loss events above a threshold (typically ₹10,000 or USD 10,000). Key examples for banks: rogue trader losses = internal fraud; phishing attacks = external fraud; mis-selling = category 4; IT outage = category 6.",
        highlight: "7 Basel OpRisk categories | Legal risk: included | Strategic/reputational: excluded | LDC database mandatory | BIA/TSA/IMA for capital"
