        body: "Government Securities (G-Secs) are debt instruments issued by the Central or State Government to finance their fiscal deficits. Central Government instruments: (1) Dated G-Secs — fixed or floating rate coupon bonds with original maturity > 1 year (2–40 years). Largest component of India's debt market. SLR-eligible. (2) Treasury Bills (T-Bills) — zero coupon, maturities 91/182/364 days. SLR-eligible. (3) Floating Rate Bonds (FRBs) — coupon linked to 91-day T-Bill rate or FBIL MIBOR + spread. Protects investors from rate risk. (4) Sovereign Gold Bonds (SGBs) — gold-linked, 8-year maturity, 2.5% fixed coupon + gold price appreciation. State Government instruments: State Development Loans (SDLs) — tenor 10–30 years, typically carry a spread of 25–100 bps over G-Secs of comparable maturity. SLR-eligible. Issued via auctions conducted by RBI.",
