        body: "Interest rate derivatives allow banks and corporates to hedge or manage exposure to interest rate movements. Three key instruments: Forward Rate Agreement (FRA): an OTC contract locking in a future interest rate for a specified period. Buyer pays fixed rate; receives floating rate. If rates rise above FRA rate → buyer profits. Used to hedge borrowing costs. Interest Rate Futures (IRF): exchange-traded (NSE) standardised contracts on 91-day T-Bills or 10-year G-Secs. Used for hedging bond portfolio price risk. Mark-to-market daily. Interest Rate Swap (IRS): exchange of fixed-rate cash flows for floating-rate cash flows (or vice versa) over an agreed tenor. Most common: plain vanilla fixed-for-floating IRS. Notional amount is not exchanged — only net interest differences. Priced using Mumbai Interbank Forward Offer Rate (MIFOR) or MIBOR-OIS.",
        highlight: "FRA: locks future rate (OTC) | IRF: exchange-traded, G-Sec/T-Bill based | IRS: fixed vs floating exchange, notional not exchanged"
