        body: "Interest Rate Risk in the Banking Book (IRRBB) is the risk that changes in interest rates adversely affect the bank's net interest income (NII) and economic value of equity (EVE) arising from banking book positions (loans, deposits, bonds in HTM/AFS — not trading book). Four sub-types: (1) Repricing Risk — mismatch in timing of repricing between assets and liabilities (most common). (2) Yield Curve Risk — non-parallel shifts — short rates rise more than long rates, or vice versa (curve steepening/flattening). (3) Basis Risk — imperfect correlation between reference rates — e.g., MCLR-linked assets vs. MIBOR-linked liabilities. (4) Optionality Risk — embedded options in banking products: prepayment of loans (borrower's option), early withdrawal of deposits (customer's option). RBI IRRBB Guidelines (2010, revised 2022) require banks to measure and monitor IRRBB via gap analysis, NII sensitivity, and EVE analysis.",
