        body: "Stress testing evaluates a bank's resilience to exceptional but plausible adverse events. Unlike VaR (which focuses on normal market conditions), stress tests capture tail risks and black-swan scenarios. Types: (1) Sensitivity Analysis: one-factor shock — e.g., NPA ratio doubles, yield rises 300 bps. (2) Scenario Analysis: multi-factor simultaneous shocks — e.g., GDP falls 4%, NPA triples, yields rise 200 bps, FPI outflows. (3) Reverse Stress Testing: identifies what scenario would render the bank unviable (CRAR falls to zero or liquidity exhausted). Required by RBI and Basel Pillar 2. ICAAP must include at minimum 3 scenarios: Baseline, Adverse, Severe. RBI's System-wide Macro Stress Test: annual exercise using FSDC/FSR data — tests banking system under RBI-specified macro scenarios.",
        highlight: "Sensitivity: 1 factor | Scenario: multi-factor | Reverse: what makes bank fail | ICAAP: 3 scenarios (base/adverse/severe) | RBI: annual system-wide test"
