        kind: "pillars",
        title: "Decomposing Bank Profitability",
        pillars: [
          { e: "📊", n: "Du Pont Analysis for Banks", d: "ROE = ROA × Equity Multiplier (= Total Assets / Equity). Higher leverage amplifies ROE. ROA = NIM + Non-Interest Income / Assets − Cost / Assets − Provisions / Assets − Tax / Assets. Decomposition identifies drivers of profitability vs. peers." },
          { e: "💰", n: "Cost-to-Income Ratio", d: "CIR = Operating Expenses / Net Income (NII + Other Income). Lower is better — reflects operating efficiency. PSBs: 45–55%; efficient private banks: 35–45%. Rising CIR → opex growing faster than income → profitability squeeze." },
          { e: "🎯", n: "RAROC — Risk-Adjusted View", d: "RAROC = (Net Interest Income + Fees − Operating Costs − Expected Loss) / Economic Capital. Business lines with RAROC > Cost of Capital (hurdle rate) create value. RAROC < hurdle rate → destroys shareholder value. Used for credit pricing and capital allocation decisions." }
        ]
