        body: "The Negotiable Instruments Act (NI Act) 1881 governs three types of negotiable instruments: (1) Promissory Note (PN): an unconditional promise in writing by the maker to pay a definite sum to the payee. (2) Bill of Exchange (BoE): an unconditional order in writing by the drawer directing the drawee to pay a specified sum to the payee. (3) Cheque: a bill of exchange drawn on a specified banker, payable on demand. A 'negotiable instrument' can be transferred by endorsement (signed on back) + delivery. The holder in due course (HDC) gets better title than the transferor — this is the essence of negotiability. Key NI Act provisions: Section 6 — definition of cheque; Section 9 — holder in due course; Section 118 — presumptions (consideration, date, endorsement are presumed valid until proved otherwise).",
        highlight: "PN: promise to pay | BoE: order to pay | Cheque: BoE on banker, payable on demand | HDC: gets free title | Sec 118: presumptions"
