        body: "The Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA) 1999 replaced FERA 1973, shifting from a criminal to a civil enforcement framework. FERA treated forex violations as criminal offences (burden of proof on accused); FEMA treats them as civil contraventions (adjudicator's proceeding, penalties). Key provisions: Section 3 — restrictions on dealings in foreign exchange (only through authorised persons). Section 4 — prohibition on holding foreign exchange outside India without permission (residents). Section 5 — Current Account Transactions: largely permitted with few restrictions. Section 6 — Capital Account Transactions: regulated by RBI rules; RBI may prohibit/restrict. Section 10 — authorised persons (AD banks, FFMCs). Section 13 — penalties for contravention: up to 3× amount involved or ₹2 Lakh (higher of the two) + ₹5,000/day for continuing violation. Section 14 — power to arrest (only Enforcement Directorate). Appellate Tribunal for Foreign Exchange (ATFE) hears appeals.",
