        body: "A mortgage is the transfer of an interest in specific immovable property for the purpose of securing a loan or obligation (Section 58, Transfer of Property Act 1882). The mortgagor (borrower) creates the mortgage; the mortgagee (bank) has the interest. Key types: (1) Simple Mortgage: mortgagor personally bound; no possession transfer; bank must go to court to enforce by sale (foreclosure). (2) Mortgage by Conditional Sale: mortgagor ostensibly sells property on condition that on repayment, sale becomes void. (3) Usufructuary Mortgage: mortgagor delivers possession; bank collects rents and profits until debt paid. (4) English Mortgage: mortgagee gets full property ownership conditionally; most rights to bank; bank can sell without court if mortgagor defaults. (5) Equitable Mortgage (Mortgage by Deposit of Title Deeds): borrower deposits original title deeds with bank — creates equitable charge. No registration required (in notified cities). Most common for home loans in India.",
