        body: "The Limitation Act 1963 prescribes the time period within which legal proceedings must be instituted. After expiry of limitation period, the claim is time-barred — court cannot entertain the suit. Key limitation periods relevant to banking: Recovery of money advanced on loan: 3 years from the date of default or date the loan became payable. Recovery on mortgage (simple mortgage): 12 years from date debt became due. Recovery on mortgage (English/equitable): 12 years. Enforcement of decree (from court): 12 years from decree date. Bills of Exchange/Promissory Note: 3 years from date of maturity/dishonour. Cheque dishonour (Section 138 complaint): 1 month from expiry of 15-day notice period. SARFAESI action: follows limitation for mortgage (12 years for secured debt). DRT claim: governed by Recovery of Debts Act — no express limitation, but courts apply equitable limitation principles.",
