        body: "A Power of Attorney (PoA) is a legal document by which one person (principal/grantor) authorises another person (attorney/agent) to act on their behalf. Governed by the Powers of Attorney Act 1882. Types: General PoA — broad authority to manage all affairs (banking, property, legal matters). Special PoA — limited to specific acts or transactions (e.g., sell a particular property, operate a specific bank account). Irrevocable PoA — created for security/consideration (e.g., when purchaser gets PoA to protect their interest in property) — cannot be revoked unilaterally. Durable PoA — remains valid even if grantor becomes mentally incapacitated (concept from US law; not formally recognized in India — PoA generally lapses on incapacity). For banking transactions: PoA must be executed on non-judicial stamp paper, attested (witnessed), and registered if it relates to immovable property transactions.",
