        body: "The Insolvency & Bankruptcy Code 2016 (IBC) created a time-bound, market-driven insolvency resolution framework, replacing the earlier patchwork of SICA, BIFR, and the winding-up provisions of the Companies Act. For banks, IBC is the primary mechanism for large NPA resolution. It consolidates insolvency law for individuals, firms, and corporates under one code and established the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Board of India (IBBI) as regulator. Key thresholds: minimum default for corporate CIRP = ₹1 crore (raised from ₹1 lakh in March 2020). CIRP timeline: 180 days + 90 days extension + litigation time; hard cap 330 days. IBC Amendment 2021 introduced Pre-Packaged Insolvency Resolution Process (PPIRP) for MSMEs: default threshold ₹10 lakh (lower than regular ₹1 crore); debtor submits a base resolution plan along with the application itself; timeline 120 days (much faster than CIRP 330 days); Swiss Challenge mechanism — third parties can submit competing plans; debtor remains in control (debtor-in-possession model). PPIRP under Sections 54A–54P.",
        highlight: "CIRP: 330 days max | CoC: 66% vote | Sec 7: financial creditor | Sec 29A: promoter bar | PPIRP (MSME): 120 days, ₹10L threshold, debtor-in-possession"
