        body: "The Information Technology Act, 2000 (amended 2008) provides the legal backbone for electronic transactions, digital signatures, and cyber crime prosecution in India. For banking, IT Act is critical for: (1) legal validity of electronic contracts and e-signatures, (2) liability of intermediaries (banks as network service providers), (3) cyber crime offences against banking systems. Section 66C (identity theft — using another's electronic signature/password), Section 66D (cheating by personation using computer — phishing/vishing), and Section 43A (compensation for body corporates failing to protect data) are most relevant to banks.",
        highlight: "Digital Signature | Sec 43A | Sec 66C | Sec 66D | Electronic Evidence | CERT-In | Cyber Crime"
