        body: "Capital structure is the mix of debt and equity a firm uses to finance its assets. The central question: is there an OPTIMAL debt-equity ratio that minimises WACC and maximises firm value? Modigliani-Miller (MM) Theorem (1958, no taxes): capital structure is IRRELEVANT — firm value determined by asset returns, not financing mix. MM with taxes (1963): debt has value because interest is tax-deductible (debt tax shield). Trade-off Theory: firms balance debt tax shield against financial distress costs to find optimal leverage. Pecking Order Theory: firms prefer internal funds → debt → equity (to minimise information asymmetry costs).",
        highlight: "MM Irrelevance | Debt Tax Shield | Trade-off Theory | Pecking Order | Financial Distress | Optimal Leverage"
