        body: "Dividend policy determines how much of a firm's earnings are distributed as dividends versus retained for reinvestment. Two schools: (1) Dividend Relevance — Gordon's Model and Walter's Model argue dividends matter to shareholders and affect firm value. (2) Dividend Irrelevance — MM Theorem (1961) argues that in perfect markets, dividend policy is irrelevant because investors can create homemade dividends. In practice, dividends signal financial health, attract income investors, and are subject to tax — making policy real-world relevant. Key metrics: Dividend Payout Ratio, Dividend Yield, Dividend Per Share, Retention Ratio.",
