    steps: [
      {
        kind: "concept",
        title: "Escrow: Controlling Project Cash Flows",
        body: "In project finance, lenders cannot rely on the SPV management to voluntarily service debt — they use escrow accounts and waterfall structures to control cash flows contractually. All project revenues are deposited into a trust-held Revenue Escrow Account. A contractual Waterfall specifies the exact order in which funds are disbursed from the escrow: first O&M expenses (to keep the project running), then debt service (lenders paid before equity), then DSRA top-up, then equity distributions. This ensures lenders are paid ahead of sponsors regardless of who manages the SPV. Debenture Trust Deeds (DTD) hold security on behalf of all lenders collectively.",
        highlight: "Revenue Escrow | Waterfall | DSRA | TRA | DTD | Trustee | Cash Lock-up | Sub-accounts"
      },
      {
        kind: "pillars",
        title: "Escrow & Waterfall Structure",
        pillars: [
          { e: "🏦", n: "Trust & Retention Account", d: "TRA: Designated bank account (often with a leading lender) where ALL project revenues are deposited. No SPV director can directly access funds. Managed by a Trustee (often SBI Cap Trustee, IDBI Trusteeship)." },
          { e: "💧", n: "Waterfall", d: "Priority order: (1) O&M Costs, (2) Debt Service (interest + scheduled principal), (3) DSRA top-up to 6-month DS, (4) Major Maintenance Reserve, (5) Tax payment, (6) Equity distributions. Lenders rank above equity — always paid first." },
          { e: "🔒", n: "Cash Lock-up", d: "If DSCR < trigger level (e.g., <1.10×): no equity distribution permitted. All cash above O&M + debt service is locked in the TRA. Forces SPV to retain cash buffer during stress. Prevents asset stripping by sponsors." },
          { e: "🛡️", n: "DSRA", d: "Debt Service Reserve Account: sub-account within TRA. Funded to 6-month debt service level. If main account insufficient → DSRA used. If DSRA drawn down → must be topped up before equity distributions resume." },
          { e: "📄", n: "DTD", d: "Debenture Trust Deed: legal instrument where SPV creates security in favour of Trustee for all lenders. Trustee enforces security on behalf of lenders collectively. Simpler than each bank holding separate security." },
          { e: "🔑", n: "Step-in Rights", d: "If SPV defaults → lenders can 'step in' (through the concession agreement) to manage or replace the O&M contractor. Protects lenders from SPV management failure. Government in concession agreement typically allows lenders to install replacement operator." }
        ]
      },
      {
        kind: "scenario",
        title: "Waterfall in a Stress Month",
        problem: "A toll road SPV has monthly toll revenue of ₹15 crore. Monthly obligations: O&M = ₹3 Cr, Debt Service = ₹12 Cr, DSRA top-up needed = ₹2 Cr. Calculate distributions and identify if equity gets any payment.",
        steps: [
          "Total Revenue = ₹15 crore (all deposited into TRA).",
          "Step 1 — O&M: Pay ₹3 Cr. TRA balance = ₹15 − ₹3 = ₹12 Cr.",
          "Step 2 — Debt Service: Pay ₹12 Cr. TRA balance = ₹12 − ₹12 = ₹0 Cr.",
          "Step 3 — DSRA top-up: ₹2 Cr needed but TRA = ₹0. DSRA is drawn down by ₹2 Cr to cover deficit.",
          "Step 4 — Equity distribution: TRA is empty. DSRA has been drawn (needs to be topped up before equity can flow). NO equity distribution this month.",
          "Next month priority: before debt service payment, DSRA must be replenished. Equity distributions locked until DSRA is fully topped up.",
          "This month's DSCR = CFADS/DS. If toll = ₹15 Cr - ₹3 Cr O&M = ₹12 Cr CFADS, DS = ₹12 Cr → DSCR = 1.0× → tight but not a default (yet)."
        ],
        verdict: "✅ Waterfall protects lenders — O&M and DS paid fully. DSRA used. Equity gets zero. DSCR 1.0× — monitor closely"
      },
      {
        kind: "quiz",
        question: "In a project finance waterfall, which payment typically has the HIGHEST priority (paid first from project revenues)?",
        opts: ["Equity distributions to sponsors", "Debt service (interest + principal) to lenders", "Operating and maintenance (O&M) costs to keep the project running", "DSRA top-up and major maintenance reserve"],
        correct: 2,
        why: "In a standard project finance waterfall, Operating and Maintenance (O&M) costs are paid FIRST — before debt service and before equity. This is because the project must remain operational to generate any revenue at all; if O&M is not paid, the project stops running and lenders receive nothing. The typical waterfall order is: (1) O&M Costs, (2) Debt Service, (3) DSRA top-up, (4) Major Maintenance Reserve, (5) Taxes, (6) Equity distributions. Equity is always last — reflecting the residual, higher-risk nature of equity capital."
      }
    ]
