      {
        kind: "concept",
        title: "Credit Risk Components: The Basel Building Blocks",
        body: "Credit risk is the risk of loss arising from a borrower's failure to meet financial obligations. Basel II/III framework decomposes credit risk into four parameters: PD (Probability of Default) — likelihood the borrower defaults in 1 year; LGD (Loss Given Default) — percentage of exposure lost if default occurs; EAD (Exposure at Default) — outstanding amount at time of default; M (Effective Maturity) — higher maturity = more risk. Expected Loss (EL) = PD × LGD × EAD. Capital is held for Unexpected Loss (UL) = difference between worst-case loss (at 99.9% confidence) and EL. These parameters form the foundation of both Internal Ratings Based (IRB) capital calculations and risk-adjusted pricing (RAROC).",
        highlight: "PD | LGD | EAD | Maturity | EL | UL | Basel IRB | RAROC | Credit Rating | Default Definition"
      },
      {
        kind: "pillars",
        title: "Four Credit Risk Parameters",
        pillars: [
          { e: "📉", n: "PD (Probability of Default)", d: "1-year probability that borrower defaults. Range: 0.01% (AAA) to 100% (already defaulted). Estimated from: internal rating history, external agency ratings, market-implied PD (CDS spreads). Basel default definition: 90 DPD OR unlikely to pay." },
          { e: "💸", n: "LGD (Loss Given Default)", d: "Percentage of EAD lost if default occurs. LGD = 1 − Recovery Rate. Depends on: collateral type (residential property → LGD 20-40%; unsecured → LGD 50-75%), seniority, and workout efficiency. LGD is downturn LGD (stressed conditions)." },
          { e: "💰", n: "EAD (Exposure at Default)", d: "Outstanding amount at time of default. For term loans: usually close to current outstanding. For revolving credit (overdraft, credit card): EAD > current outstanding (borrower draws more before default). Credit Conversion Factor (CCF) applied." },
          { e: "⏰", n: "Maturity (M)", d: "Effective maturity (max 5 years in IRB). Longer maturity = higher risk (more time for credit quality to deteriorate). Maturity Adjustment added to capital formula: longer tenor assets require more capital. Also called 'b' adjustment factor." },
          { e: "📊", n: "EL vs UL", d: "EL = PD × LGD × EAD — priced into loan margin (spread). UL = losses at 99.9% VaR − EL — covered by regulatory/economic capital. Banks must hold capital for unexpected losses, not expected ones (EL is 'cost of doing business')." },
          { e: "🔢", n: "RAROC", d: "Risk-Adjusted Return on Capital = (Revenue − EL − Operating Cost) / Economic Capital. Measures whether a loan earns above the cost of capital. If RAROC > hurdle rate → value-creating. Used for credit pricing and performance measurement." }
        ]
      },
      {
        kind: "scenario",
        title: "Expected Loss Calculation",
        problem: "A bank has a ₹10 crore term loan to a BBB-rated corporate. Internal PD = 0.5%, LGD = 45% (secured by property), EAD = ₹10 crore. Calculate EL, and determine the minimum loan spread needed if bank's cost of funds = 7%, opex = 0.5%, target RAROC = 15%, Economic Capital = 8% of EAD.",
        steps: [
          "EL = PD × LGD × EAD = 0.5% × 45% × ₹10 Cr = 0.225% × ₹10 Cr = ₹0.0225 Cr = ₹2.25 lakh.",
          "EL as % of EAD = 0.225% (this is the credit cost to be priced in).",
          "Economic Capital = 8% × ₹10 Cr = ₹0.80 crore.",
          "Required return on EC = RAROC × EC = 15% × ₹0.80 Cr = ₹0.12 Cr = ₹12 lakh.",
          "Minimum spread = EL + OpEx + EC cost = 0.225% + 0.5% + (12 lakh/1000 lakh × 100%) = 0.225% + 0.5% + 1.2% = 1.925%.",
          "Minimum loan rate = Cost of funds + Minimum spread = 7% + 1.925% ≈ 8.93%. Bank should price this loan at ≥9% to meet RAROC target."
        ],
        verdict: "✅ EL = ₹2.25 lakh. Minimum spread = 1.93%. Minimum loan rate ≈ 9% to cover EL + OpEx + required EC return"
      },
      {
        kind: "quiz",
        question: "Under Basel II/III, Expected Loss (EL) in credit risk is calculated as:",
        opts: ["EL = PD + LGD + EAD", "EL = PD × LGD × EAD", "EL = Capital × RWA × PD", "EL = LGD × (1 − PD) × EAD"],
        correct: 1,
        why: "Expected Loss (EL) = PD × LGD × EAD. This is the fundamental Basel credit risk formula. PD is the probability that the borrower defaults; LGD is the fraction of EAD lost if default occurs; EAD is the exposure at the time of default. EL represents the average annual credit loss expected from a loan — it is priced into the loan's interest spread. Capital is held for Unexpected Losses (UL) — the losses that exceed EL at a high confidence level (99.9% under Basel IRB approach)."
      }
