        body: "Credit derivatives are instruments that allow the transfer of credit risk from one party to another without transferring the underlying asset. Key instruments: Credit Default Swap (CDS) — the most liquid credit derivative: protection buyer pays periodic premium; protection seller pays face value if reference entity defaults. Collateralised Debt Obligation (CDO) — structured product that tranches credit risk from a portfolio. Credit-linked Note (CLN) — funded credit derivative. Banks use credit derivatives for: (1) hedging credit concentrations, (2) synthetic portfolio creation, (3) regulatory capital relief (though with restrictions). CDS market is primarily OTC and regulated by ISDA documentation.",
        highlight: "CDS | CDO | CLN | Protection Buyer | Protection Seller | Reference Entity | Tranching | ISDA | Credit Event"
