        body: "Credit stress testing simulates how a bank's credit portfolio would perform under severe but plausible economic scenarios. It answers: 'If the economy deteriorates significantly, do we have enough capital?' Credit stress tests involve: (1) translating macro scenarios into credit risk parameter changes (PD/LGD increases), (2) computing stressed credit losses, (3) assessing impact on capital ratios. RBI's Financial Stability Report includes system-wide credit stress test results. Individual banks must conduct credit stress tests as part of ICAAP. Reverse credit stress testing identifies what credit event (default rate, sector collapse) would cause the bank to breach minimum capital — revealing breaking points.",
