          { e: "📄", n: "Resolution Plan", d: "RBI/Resolution Authority prepares. Shows how bank can be resolved without systemic disruption: transfer of critical functions to bridge bank, sale to acquirer, bail-in of subordinated creditors. Aim: protect depositors, maintain payment systems." },
          { e: "💰", n: "Bail-in vs Bail-out", d: "Bail-out: government capital injection (taxpayer-funded, creates moral hazard). Bail-in: creditors and shareholders absorb losses before taxpayer money is used. G20 reform post-2008: move from bail-out to bail-in. Basel AT1 and Tier 2 instruments include bail-in triggers." },
          { e: "🏦", n: "TLAC/MREL", d: "Total Loss-Absorbing Capacity (TLAC) for G-SIBs: minimum 16% of RWA (20% by 2022) in bail-inable instruments. MREL (Minimum Requirement for Eligible Liabilities): EU equivalent. Ensures resolution is funded by creditors, not taxpayers." },
          { e: "🇮🇳", n: "India Framework", d: "FRDI Bill (withdrawn, re-introduced): proposed resolution framework for banks and financial institutions. Currently: RBI has powers under BR Act (Sec 45) for amalgamation/moratorium. IBC (FSP Amendment 2019) for NBFC resolution. Bank resolution mechanism evolving." },
          { e: "🔵", n: "Critical Functions", d: "Identified in resolution plans: payment services, deposit-taking, trade finance. Must be preserved even during resolution — using bridge bank, asset sale, or operational continuity agreements. Society cannot survive disruption to payment systems." }
