        body: "AI (Artificial Intelligence) uses algorithms to simulate human intelligence; ML (Machine Learning) is a subset where models learn from data without explicit programming. Banking applications: (1) Credit Scoring — ML models (XGBoost, Random Forest) on alternative data (telecom, utility, UPI patterns) for thin-file customers; (2) Fraud Detection — real-time anomaly detection, card fraud alerts, behavioural analytics; (3) Chatbots/Virtual Assistants — NLP-based (SBI YONO Mitra, HDFC EVA, Axis Aha!); (4) AML/KYC — graph analytics for network analysis, transaction monitoring, suspicious activity detection; (5) Credit portfolio management — early warning systems (EWS), NPA prediction; (6) Robo-advisory — automated portfolio rebalancing, SIP recommendations. Risks: Model Risk (wrong predictions → mis-selling or unfair lending), Explainability (LIME, SHAP for black-box models), Data bias (biased training data → discriminatory credit decisions), Adversarial attacks. RBI discussion paper on AI/ML governance 2024 emphasises model governance, explainability, and fairness.",
        highlight: "Credit scoring (alternative data) | Fraud detection (real-time) | AML graph analytics | Model risk: bias + explainability | SHAP/LIME"
