        body: "India's Digital Personal Data Protection (DPDP) Act 2023 (enacted August 2023, rules pending) establishes comprehensive data protection. Key principles: Lawful basis for processing (consent/legitimate use); Purpose limitation; Data minimisation; Accuracy; Storage limitation; Integrity & confidentiality; Accountability. Data Principal = individual (customer); Data Fiduciary = entity processing data (bank). Consent: free, specific, informed, unconditional, unambiguous — withdrawable at any time. Significant Data Fiduciaries (SDFs): notified by government — higher obligations (DPO appointment, DPIA, audits). Rights of Data Principal: Right to information, Right to correction/erasure, Right to grievance redressal, Right to nominate. Penalties: Up to ₹250 crore for breach of obligations. Data Localisation: RBI mandates payment data to be stored only in India; DPDP Act does not mandate general localisation but allows cross-border transfer to approved countries. Banks also comply with GDPR for EU customers. Data Protection Officer (DPO): mandatory for SDFs and likely for banks.",
