        body: "Kirkpatrick's Four-Level Model (1959, updated with son James as 'New World Kirkpatrick Model'): Level 1 — Reaction: Did participants like the training? (feedback forms, happy sheets — easy to collect, often misleading); Level 2 — Learning: Did they learn? (pre/post tests, skills assessment, certification results — JAIIB/CAIIB pass rates); Level 3 — Behaviour: Did they apply learning on the job? (supervisor observation 3-6 months post training, 360° feedback, mystery shopping for customer service training — harder to measure); Level 4 — Results: Did it impact business? (NPA reduction after credit training, fraud incidents after security training, customer satisfaction after service training — hardest, most valuable). Phillips' ROI Model adds Level 5: ROI = (Net Training Benefits − Training Cost) / Training Cost × 100. Isolation techniques: control group, trend analysis, estimation by participants. Most banks measure L1 (always) and L2 (often); L3-L4 rarely — gap in HR analytics maturity.",
