        title: "Capturing and Sharing Organisational Knowledge",
        body: "Knowledge Management (KM) = systematic process of capturing, organising, sharing, and applying organisational knowledge. Tacit knowledge: personal, experience-based, hard to articulate (expert credit officer's 'gut feel' for borrower quality); Explicit knowledge: codified, documented, transferable (RBI circular, credit policy manual). Nonaka & Takeuchi's SECI Model: Socialisation (T→T: shared experience), Externalisation (T→E: tacit to explicit — documenting best practices), Combination (E→E: combining explicit knowledge), Internalisation (E→T: explicit to tacit — learning by doing). KM tools in banks: knowledge portals/wikis (HDFC, ICICI internal knowledge bases), communities of practice (CoP — circle of credit officers sharing learnings), case databases (loan decisions, legal precedents), Lessons Learned repositories. Learning Organisation (Senge, 1990 — 'The Fifth Discipline'): 5 disciplines: Systems Thinking, Personal Mastery, Mental Models, Shared Vision, Team Learning. PSB challenge: knowledge loss due to mass retirements (70s-80s batch retiring); structured Knowledge Transfer (KT) programmes essential.",
