        body: "Industrial Relations (IR) = the relationships between employers, employees, their representative organisations (unions), and the state (government/law). Dunlop's IR System Model (1958): three actors — employers (management), workers (unions), and government; web of rules (substantive = pay/working conditions; procedural = how disputes resolved) governs the system; context (technology, market, power balance) shapes IR. IR Climate = overall state of labour-management relations: Cooperative vs Adversarial. Indicators of poor IR climate: frequent strikes, high grievances, low productivity, high absenteeism. IR in Indian banking: governed by Industrial Disputes Act 1947, Trade Unions Act 1926, Banking Companies (Acquisition and Transfer of Undertakings) Acts, bipartite settlements. Unique banking IR features: public interest in bank services (no prolonged strike allowed easily), strong union power historically (especially in PSBs), state as owner in PSBs (complex tripartite relationship), wage settlement through IBA. Code on Industrial Relations 2020: consolidates 3 labour laws (ID Act, TU Act, Industrial Employment Standing Orders Act) — being implemented.",
