        body: "Collective Bargaining (CB) = process of negotiation between employer/management and trade union to determine terms and conditions of employment and procedures for resolving disputes. Types: Conjunctive (distributive — win-lose, fixed pie, typical in wage negotiations), Cooperative (integrative — expand pie; problem-solving; productivity bargaining). CB in Indian banks: IBA + UFBU = bipartite settlement every 5 years; in-between, individual bank management + local unions for local settlements. Third-party dispute resolution: (1) Conciliation: voluntary, facilitated by Conciliation Officer (IDA Sec 11-16); no binding power; widely used; (2) Voluntary Arbitration: both parties agree to refer to arbitrator; binding award; Sec 10A IDA; faster than tribunals; (3) Compulsory Adjudication: government refers to Labour Court/Tribunal; binding; used when conciliation fails and dispute is serious. International: ILO conventions on collective bargaining (Convention 98, 154) — India has partially ratified. Code on Industrial Relations 2020 — simplifies CB process, introduces sole negotiating union/negotiating council.",
