        kind: "concept",
        title: "LAF: Managing Day-to-Day Liquidity",
        body: "Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF): introduced by RBI in 1999-2000 (Narasimham Committee II); operational since 2000. LAF allows RBI to inject or absorb short-term liquidity on a daily basis to keep short-term market rates (call money, T-bill) within the policy corridor. Operations: (1) Repo: RBI injects funds — banks sell G-secs to RBI with agreement to repurchase (i.e., borrow from RBI); currently 14-day Variable Rate Repo (VRR) is the main instrument; fixed rate repos also conducted; (2) SDF (Standing Deposit Facility): RBI absorbs funds — banks park excess reserves with RBI at SDF rate (repo−25bps); no collateral required; (3) Variable Rate Reverse Repo (VRRR): RBI absorbs excess liquidity via competitive auction. LAF corridor: SDF rate (floor) ← Repo rate (policy rate) → MSF rate (ceiling); spread = ±25 bps symmetric corridor. Corridor logic: call money rate should stay within corridor; if rates go above MSF, banks borrow from RBI at MSF; if rates go below SDF, banks park with RBI via SDF — corridor constrains market rates. Daily LAF operations: announced in money market circular; auction for repos and VRRRs; settlement same-day via RTGS. CRR maintenance: fortnightly; daily minimum 90%; shortfall → penalty = bank rate + 5% on shortfall.",
        highlight: "LAF since 2000 | Corridor: SDF (floor)−Repo (policy)−MSF (ceiling) ±25bps | 14-day VRR main instrument | VRRR absorbs excess | CRR: fortnightly, 90% daily min"
