        body: "Open Market Operations (OMOs): RBI buys or sells government securities in the secondary market to manage durable (structural, long-term) liquidity — distinct from LAF (short-term, day-to-day). OMO Purchase (injection): RBI buys G-secs from banks → bank accounts credited with reserves → durable liquidity injected → system moves from deficit to surplus → typically depresses G-sec yields; OMO Sale (withdrawal): RBI sells G-secs → bank reserves debited → liquidity withdrawn. Triggers: (1) Seasonal liquidity deficit (currency demand in festive season); (2) Capital inflows creating excess liquidity; (3) Government borrowing crowding out — OMO purchase stabilises yields; (4) Monetary policy transmission — OMO purchase + rate cut = reinforced easing. G-SAP (Government Securities Acquisition Programme): announced May 2021; RBI's commitment to buy ₹1 lakh crore G-secs in Q1 FY22 in a pre-announced calendar (like QE); provides forward guidance on yields; reduces uncertainty; discontinued as liquidity surplus normalised. Simultaneous Purchase and Sale (Twist Operation / 'Operation Twist'): RBI buys long-term G-secs (30Y) and simultaneously sells short-term (91-day T-Bills) → flattens yield curve; reduces long-term borrowing cost without changing short-term rates. Impact on banks: OMO purchase → G-sec prices rise → MTM gains for banks' investment portfolio.",
