        body: "Flexible Inflation Targeting (FIT): adopted in India via agreement between RBI and GoI in February 2015; legally embedded in RBI Act via 2016 amendment (Sections 45ZA-45ZL). Key elements: (1) Nominal Anchor: CPI (combined — rural + urban) = 4% ± 2% (range: 2%-6%); GoI sets target for 5 years in consultation with RBI; (2) 'Flexible' = growth is considered alongside inflation — not purely inflation-focused (like Bundesbank); (3) Instrument independence: RBI has full discretion on how to achieve the target (repo rate, CRR, OMO, FX intervention); (4) Transparency: MPC minutes, MPR, public vote disclosure; (5) Accountability: breach → report to government. Headline vs Core CPI: FIT targets headline CPI (includes food and fuel); core CPI (ex-food-fuel) better reflects demand; RBI watches both. Food inflation challenge: food = 39% of CPI basket; highly volatile (monsoon, supply); monetary policy less effective for food inflation (supply-side). FIT globally: pioneered by New Zealand (1990); adopted by UK (1992), Canada, Australia; India (2016). Benefits: credibility (inflation expectations anchored), transparency, predictability. Critics: too tight (sacrifices growth for low inflation); food inflation beyond monetary policy's reach.",
