        body: "Risk-Based Supervision (RBS) replaces the traditional transaction-based inspection approach with a forward-looking, risk-focused framework. India's evolution: traditional Annual Financial Inspection (AFI) using CAMEL framework → RBS introduced in 2003 → SPARC (Supervisory Programme for Assessment of Risk and Capital) launched 2012. SPARC framework: continuous, forward-looking, risk-focused assessment. Components: (1) Risk Profiling: each bank assigned a risk profile based on inherent risks (credit, market, liquidity, operational, IT, business strategy, legal) and control effectiveness → risk matrix; (2) Supervisory Rating: supervisory comfort score (1-worst to 5-best) based on CAMEL-S (adding 'S' for Systems and control/Sensitivity); (3) Supervisory Planning: intensity of supervision tailored to risk profile; high-risk banks get more frequent inspections; (4) Off-site monitoring: OSMOS quarterly reviews, CIMS data analysis, early warning triggers. Off-site indicators: GNPA ratio, CRAR, liquidity ratios (LCR, NSFR), Credit Concentration, Profitability (ROA/ROE), ALM gaps. Supervisory colleges: for multinational banks operating in India — RBI coordinates with foreign home country supervisors. RBI SPARC: bank's risk matrix reviewed annually; all departments (credit, market, operational, IT, legal, HR) risk-assessed; Board engagement on top risks.",
